column124:
13/Feb/19 11:58 AM;benjamincburns;I'm a bit late to the party, but I notice you're discussing stateful requests (e.g. \{{eth_newFilter}} and friends). I'm pleased to say that the Ethereum community seems to be quickly moving away from these stateful methods. Last I checked, Infura doesn't support them, and section 6.3 the [current EEA specification|https://entethalliance.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/EEA_Enterprise_Ethereum_Client_Specification_V2.pdf] drops the requirement for Enterprise Ethereum clients to support any stateful RPC methods.

I generally advise people writing Ethereum applications today to use a WebSockets transport rather than HTTP, and to make use of the newer [RPC PUB/SUB API|https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/wiki/RPC-PUB-SUB]. This not only allows for a more efficient push-based subscription mechanism for logs, blocks, and transactions, but it also makes it so that the lifecycle of those subscriptions is tied directly to the lifecycle of the application client's connection. That is, when the connection closes the node no longer needs to service the outstanding subscriptions for that connection.

[Ganache|https://truffleframework.com/ganache] and [ganache-cli|https://www.npmjs.com/package/ganache-cli] have implemented these features for a while now, and I'd recommend them as a platform for experimentation to see how it works.;;;

